context: May winne of me mo fees° thus
To have mo floures, swiche seven°
In alle thinges moor mesure
He stood unnethes° seide he wordes mo
Ther fil, as it bifalleth times mo
O noble wives, ful of heigh prudence
“Of quiksilver, withouten wordes mo,°
And empten° also grete and hevy purses
Forestes, parkes° ful of wilde deer;
Whan thritty tiraunts, ful of cursednesse
For which thise woful maidens, ful of drede
¶“What sholde I mo ensamples heerof° sayn
Certein he knew of briberyes° mo°
Tel me anon, withouten wordes mo
As ye han herd; what nedeth wordes mo?
In whiche ther were mo images
And with perre° mo pinacles
And mo loves new begonne
And mo loves casuelly°
Mo discords, mo jelousies
Mo discords, mo jelousies
Mo murmurs, and mo novelries
Mo murmurs, and mo novelries
And mo dissimulacions;
And mo berdes° in two houres
And also mo renovelaunces°
Mo love-dayes° and acordes°
And eke of loves mo eschaunges°
Of songes, ful of armonie,°
Good werkes shal yow noght availe°
Han these sory creatures!
Wher thou maist most tidinges here;
Terme of his lif; what nedeth wordes mo?
And seide: “Sire, what nedeth wordes mo?
What ladies fairest been or best daunsinge
With othere rites mo; and atte laste
And cuppes ful of win, and milke and blood
Yet were me lever° houndes had me eten
I fele my limes° stark° and suffisaunt
Of scole-termes;° wiser men than thow
Upon a bench of turves,° fresh and grene
Upon hir lendes,° ful of many a gore.°
And right anon, withouten wordes mo
Withouten wordes mo, they goon to bedde
He sit him up withouten wordes mo
Sixty cubites° long, and seven in brede,°
This king of kinges proud was and elaat,°
His nailes whitter than the lilie flour
As seith my lord, so make us al good men;
And wente his wey withouten wordes mo.
¶Now, good men, God foryeve yow your trespas,°
“There been mo sterres,° God wot, than a paire!”
With angels ful of cleernesse and of light
And deintees° mo than been in my knowing.
And been of good condiciouns therto;
As make it with thise argumentes tough;
So were his dayes sory outher gladde.
To telle in short, withouten wordes mo
Tho bisy wrecches, ful of wo and drede!
Withouten wordes mo, I wol be deed.
Among the Grekes, ful of worthinesse
For which, withouten any wordes mo
Was in his nedes prest and corageous;
Who shal now trowe on any othes mo?
Of Brugges were his hosen° broun
I trowe° he hadde wives mo than oon;
And ech of hem had wives mo than two;
Of urine, and our bothe thinges smal°
For I shal telle ensamples mo than ten.
He knew of hem mo legendes and lives
Of Venus werkes worth his olde sho,°
And therwithal, he knew of mo proverbes
But now can no man see none elves mo.
